@article{ WOS:A1991FU69800002,
Author = {SERIDIBENKADDOUR, R and CHESNOY, L},
Title = {THE POLLEN RECEPTIVE SURFACE IN THE CEPHALOTAXUS-DRUPACEA SIEV AND ZUCC
   ULTRASTRUCTURAL MODIFICATIONS OF THE NUCELLUS CELLS SURROUNDING THE
   POLLEN CHAMBER DURING POLLINATION DROP SECRETION},
Journal = {BULLETIN DE LA SOCIETE BOTANIQUE DE FRANCE-LETTRES BOTANIQUES},
Year = {1991},
Volume = {138},
Number = {2},
Pages = {103-115},
Abstract = {A weakly developed pollen chamber is formed in the ovules of
   Cephalotaxus drupacea (Singh, 1961) before pollination drop exudation
   starts (Fig. 1, 2).  The distal tissue of the nucellus is disorganized
   (Fig. 3, 4) and large superficial intercellular spaces are filled up
   with heterogenous osmiophilic substances (Fig. 5).  Cells surrounding
   the chamber have typical cytological features of gland cells (Fig. 6, 7,
   8) with large periplasmic spaces containing mucilage-like substances
   (Bajon et al., 1976; Bouchet et Deysson, 1976).  In addition, cells
   walls are progressively modified during the pollination time.
   At the beginning of the secretion phase, lenticular thickenings of dark
   fibrillar material appear between the primary wall and the plasmalemma
   (Fig. 9, 10, 11).  Then, fibrillar deposits coalesce enclosing numerous
   mucilage pockets (Fig. 12, 13).  Towards the end of the drop secretion
   time, the plasmalemma is again located near the wall.  The mucilage
   pockets now appear as electron transparent areas limited by dense
   lamellae (Fig. 14, 15) which seem similar to those of the intercellular
   spaces (Fig. 5).
   PATAg staining (Thiery, 1967) reveals the polysaccharidic nature of the
   new fibrillar layer of the wall (Fig. 10, 12) and the lipidic or
   lipo-proteinic nature (Roland, 1974) of the dark lamellae (Fig. 16).  As
   far as the chemical composition of the intercellular space material is
   concerned, it can be supposed to consist in a poorly polysaccharidic and
   proteinic substance as demonstrated by treatment with trypsin and PATAg.
   Fig. 19 to 23 show slightly modifications in the mucilage network after
   treatments with trypsin or after DMSO for hemicellulose or EDTA for
   pectin solubilization (Reis and Roland, 1974; Reis, 1976).
   The nucellar top cells furnish mucilages for the pollination fluid and
   secrete a new wall layer and materials for the intercellular spaces. 
   The fact that the periplasmic spaces decrease as well as the clearing of
   the mucilage pockets after the intensive secretion, phase would support
   the view that nucellar cells are responsible for the pollination drop
   production.  However, the glycanic fraction of the fluid sugars (Table
   1) (Serkli-Benkaddour and Chesnoy, 1988) may also originate from the
   middle lamellae destruction.  Electron transparent areas were observed
   in the Walls of Chamaecyparis lawsoniana apical nucellar cells
   (Cecchi-Fiordi and Maugini, 1977).  They have been regarded as sites of
   enzymatic hydrolysis.  Our studies indicate that such structures in C.
   drupacea arise from mucilage containing pockets.  Moreover, the dark
   lamellae of the intercellular spaces and walls could be some precursors
   of suberin induced by wounding of the nucellus top (Kolmiukudy, 1981).
   The apical dissociated cells seem not unlike the Angiosperm stigmatic
   papillae but their surface is devoid of cuticle (Jensen and Fisher,
   1969).  In the nucellar spaces, the substances are very similar in their
   aspect and biochemical composition in C. drupacea and in the solid style
   of Angiosperms (Sassen, 1974; Cresti et al., 1976).  In the two cases,
   the pollen tubes will grow in these spaces.
   In a great number of Gymnosperms, the pollen grains germinate on the
   distal end of the nucellus but these structures are insufficiently known
   at the present time.  In Cupressaceae, a pollen chamber is not really
   formed but the distal tissue of the nucellus is disorganized (Seridi and
   Chesnoy, 1986).  Few studies have been devoted to the pollination drop
   composition and concentration (Mc William, 1958; Ziegler, 1969;
   Seridi-Benkaddour and Chesnoy, 1988).  Differences but also some
   similarities occur between the systematic groups of Gymnosperms.  The
   germination could be possible in the fluid of two related species
   (Mehra, 1938).  Examination of ovules often reveals dead or alive but
   not germinated pollen grains.  They can be stranger pollens included by
   the pollen drop mechanisms but inhibited by the ovule.},
